39451358e354"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note that the difference between the atomic and molecular case is simply a \
sum over the interactions of an electron with multiple nuclei rather than the \
interaction with just a single nucleus. This operator is sometimes referred \
to as the one-electron operator because it includes all of the terms that act \
only on each individual electron. In the case of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["H",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "2", "+"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "0d3c2026-d550-994a-8f9c-6fa97a3f08c2"],
 ", where there are two nuclei and one electron, we can write"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8135009957626705`*^9, 3.8135009991566205`*^9}, 
   3.81350110831454*^9, {3.8135011692309904`*^9, 3.8135012697497206`*^9}, {
   3.8135014277992926`*^9, 
   3.813501457198095*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5db3ba11-c830-7843-a464-\
c84d08de34e5"],

