Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 10.7",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Molecular orbital energy diagrams for first- and second-row diatomic \
molecules.  S. M. Blinder (March 2011) , Wolfram Demonstrations, CC BY-NC-SA \
3.0, https://demonstrations.wolfram.com/\
MolecularOrbitalsForFirstAndSecondRowDiatomicMolecules/."
}], "Affiliation",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809435027311596*^9, 3.8094350763900714`*^9}, {
   3.80943583474421*^9, 3.8094358359299717`*^9}, {3.8094472165104203`*^9, 
   3.809447281165168*^9}, {3.809510876137825*^9, 3.809510907739876*^9}, {
   3.809968073566992*^9, 3.8099681536568317`*^9}, {3.810557260250428*^9, 
   3.8105572606139913`*^9}, {3.8130835305386977`*^9, 
   3.8130836194514275`*^9}, {3.813224407772764*^9, 3.8132244817756805`*^9}, {
   3.8132354037950773`*^9, 3.813235501614183*^9}, 3.813236418234542*^9, {
   3.81351439000795*^9, 3.8135143988971663`*^9}, {3.813665905470446*^9, 
   3.8136660007466154`*^9}, {3.8136660571324577`*^9, 3.81366605723772*^9}, {
   3.8136663097257414`*^9, 3.8136664742951727`*^9}, {3.8136771452348175`*^9, 
   3.8136771995450125`*^9}, {3.9196717869243536`*^9, 3.919671787791487*^9}, {
   3.937487697391802*^9, 
   3.937487698992468*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"80422309-bd18-4615-902c-\
dee0f533f986"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "These diagrams can provide a conceptual understanding of the bonding in a \
molecule and help in predicting properties including bond order and valence \
electron spin states. Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s briefly discuss the nomenclature \
assigned to molecular orbitals in the diagrams in Figure 10.7. Molecular \
orbitals that are symmetric about the internuclear axis are known as \[Sigma] \
orbitals. There are both bonding \[Sigma] orbitals, which are designated \
simply as \[Sigma], and antibonding \[Sigma] orbitals, which are typically \
designated as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "\[Star]"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "dabd41bf-a691-4cea-ae21-06f5d5d177a8"],
 " orbitals. Alternately, orbitals can be labeled according to their symmetry \
about the midway point of the internuclear axis. If inverting the orbital \
about this point changes the sign of the wavefunction, it is labeled as \
ungerade (German for odd) or ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "u"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5fe993d7-6dbe-442c-b2fc-f6f5c07b0b6f"],
 ". If the inversion doesn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t change the sign of the orbital, \
it is labeled as gerade (German for even) or ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "g"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "3f4f35f0-36ef-40a9-acb6-f46236f50d30"],
 ". The other class of molecular orbitals for first- and second-row diatomic \
molecules are the \[Pi] orbitals, which are defined as molecular orbitals \
exhibiting a nodal plane that includes the internuclear axis. Similar to the \
\[Sigma] orbitals, there are both bonding (\[Pi] or ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Pi]", "u"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "fae59afe-bac3-4b44-af6d-8b01f54178d5"],
 ") and antibonding (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["\[Pi]", "\[Star]"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "be79d7f0-3957-48b0-9453-191b91797623"],
 " or ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Pi]", "g"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7cb7f457-1497-4762-ae5e-a92ab1744d20"],
 ") designations for this orbital class. Note that the gerade and ungerade \
labels have flipped from those of the \[Sigma] orbitals (gerade are now the \
antibonding orbitals)."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.813677671020223*^9, 3.8136777040800056`*^9}, {
   3.8136778744434776`*^9, 3.813677964425393*^9}, {3.813678060774083*^9, 
   3.8136782440276613`*^9}, {3.813678541942247*^9, 3.813678573897667*^9}, {
   3.813678605487688*^9, 3.813678654552761*^9}, {3.8136834588180995`*^9, 
   3.8136834865672874`*^9}, 3.9196718253153815`*^9, {3.919671906911668*^9, 
   3.9196719072724867`*^9}, {3.9374877164353676`*^9, 
   3.9374877172547913`*^9}, {3.9374877620393333`*^9, 
   3.937487773284704*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8395663c-003e-4c55-b231-\
d581cf059fa5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A question that may arise when examining Figure 10.7 is why molecular \
orbitals don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t arise from a combination of 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbitals, for example (i.e., we represent molecular orbitals as a \
combination of 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", not 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "). The general rule is that molecular orbitals are primarily composed of \
atomic orbitals with similar energy. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8136786704526014`*^9, 3.813678837104686*^9}, {
  3.8136852725605526`*^9, 3.81368527339931*^9}, {3.919672709649476*^9, 
  3.9196727622090254`*^9}, {3.9196728038416357`*^9, 3.919672831240782*^9}, {
  3.9196728640027533`*^9, 3.919672874206386*^9}, {3.937487778034584*^9, 
  3.9374877797976704`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"46fd47e8-ebc6-4b99-8421-\
f53d31b648ae"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A second important question posed by Figure 10.7 is how the 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals combine to give one set of \[Sigma] molecular orbitals and two \
sets of \[Pi] molecular orbitals. These new orbitals come from the relative \
orientation of the atomic ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals with respect to the internuclear axis. Remember that we have ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SubscriptBox["p", "x"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8c8910bb-349b-4102-90fb-7eaa789015b6"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SubscriptBox["p", "y"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b118f8d7-8027-46bd-a922-9c6bedc64aad"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SubscriptBox["p", "z"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "53046d59-a9de-45f9-ab79-2816b4c17b21"],
 " atomic orbitals. If we designate the internuclear axis as the ",
 StyleBox["z",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " axis (as we do by convention), then the linear combination of the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SubscriptBox["p", "z"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4f6beda7-e2e3-431c-91ea-3643ded4b969"],
 " orbitals will lie along the internuclear axis and form a set of \[Sigma] \
orbitals (see Figure 10.8). In addition, when we discuss molecular orbitals \
of heteronuclear diatomic molecules, ",
 StyleBox["ns",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox[
     RowBox[{
