Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Molecular Orbitals of Heteronuclear Diatomic Molecules", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.813944518934715*^9, 
  3.8139445298366356`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4339c385-4615-4ab1-859b-\
9b347424a546"],

Cell["\<\
Now that we have examined the molecular orbitals of homonuclear diatomic \
molecules, let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s add a layer of complexity and study \
heteronuclear diatomic molecules. We will generally follow the same procedure \
that we used in the homonuclear case, taking linear combinations of atomic \
orbitals to generate the new molecular orbitals. However, we must now address \
the question of which atomic orbitals will combine to yield the molecular \
orbitals. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814106993838205*^9, 3.8141071917215185`*^9}, {
  3.9196735939606113`*^9, 
  3.9196735955793753`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"85446ed6-1aed-4543-bc6f-\
bf24b166d147"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In general, we will employ the same general principle we examined for the \
homonuclear diatomic molecules: molecular orbitals are composed primarily of \
orbitals of similar energies. In contrast to the homonuclear case, the atomic \
orbitals of a heteronuclear diatomic do not have the same energy (i.e., a 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbital on one atom does not have the same energy as 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbital on another atom). If the difference in atomic number is small, \
these energy differences will be small, and the orbital energy diagram will \
be similar to that of a homonuclear diatomic molecule. Take the example of \
carbon monoxide, for which the molecular orbital energy diagram is shown in \
Figure 10.11. One still obtains \[Sigma] orbitals from the mixing of the C 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and O 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbitals and a combination of \[Sigma] and \[Pi] bonds from the \
mixing of the C 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and O 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbitals. However, the molecular orbitals are slightly asymmetric, \
with the O atomic orbitals contributing more strongly to the bonding \
molecular orbitals, meaning a slightly higher electron density around the \
oxygen than around the carbon in the bonding MOs. This asymmetry is \
represented visually by the slightly off-center MO positions in the diagram. \
Note that we can no longer use the ",
 StyleBox["g",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["u",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " subscripts because the orbitals are asymmetric."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.81410719394429*^9, 3.814107315766405*^9}, 
   3.8141079821751432`*^9, {3.8141080572525826`*^9, 3.8141083178664637`*^9}, {
   3.814108418071079*^9, 3.8141084648072014`*^9}, {3.9196737005193825`*^9, 
   3.91967370093832*^9}, {3.9374879063439407`*^9, 
   3.9374879209788322`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"622aa206-f0a8-4fe7-903d-\
ba72b862c6da"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

