Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 10.11",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Molecular orbital energy diagram for carbon monoxide. Wikimedia, 2008, \
Jcwf, CC BY-SA 3.0, https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:MOdiagramCO.png."
}], "Affiliation",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809435027311596*^9, 3.8094350763900714`*^9}, {
  3.80943583474421*^9, 3.8094358359299717`*^9}, {3.8094472165104203`*^9, 
  3.809447281165168*^9}, {3.809510876137825*^9, 3.809510907739876*^9}, {
  3.809968073566992*^9, 3.8099681536568317`*^9}, {3.810557260250428*^9, 
  3.8105572606139913`*^9}, {3.8130835305386977`*^9, 3.8130836194514275`*^9}, {
  3.813224407772764*^9, 3.8132244817756805`*^9}, {3.814107987969291*^9, 
  3.814108049630145*^9}, {3.9196737278819036`*^9, 3.9196737282484694`*^9}, {
  3.937487946696308*^9, 
  3.9374879485447674`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"83094088-fb2c-4abc-986a-\
7d4447d2814e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If the atomic number of the two atoms differ significantly, then the \
energies of the atomic orbitals will differ significantly, and molecular \
orbitals may then be formed by a combination of different classes of atomic \
orbitals. For example, in hydrogen fluoride, the 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbital of hydrogen (~\[Minus]0.5 hartrees) is comparable in energy \
to the 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbital of fluorine (~\[Minus]0.68 hartrees). The 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbital of fluorine is significantly lower in energy (~\[Minus]1.5 \
hartrees), so the bonding and antibonding molecular orbitals are formed \
primarily by a linear combination of the H 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and F 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals, whereas the fluorine 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " retain much of their atomic character in the molecular orbital \
approximation. The molecular orbital energy diagram for hydrogen fluoride is \
shown in Figure 10.12. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814108348923232*^9, 3.814108410344469*^9}, {
  3.814108471053722*^9, 3.814108474034797*^9}, {3.814108761465439*^9, 
  3.8141090936560683`*^9}, {3.814109302179016*^9, 3.814109303312616*^9}, {
  3.8141183391599197`*^9, 3.814118340500224*^9}, {3.919673777830041*^9, 
  3.919673778205518*^9}, {3.937487977862522*^9, 
  3.9374879787728405`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4d3109c0-7ff4-4365-9917-\
c88855c9bddf"],

