   BoxForm`ImageTag["Byte", ColorSpace -> "RGB", Interleaving -> True],
   Selectable->False],
  AspectRatio->Full,
  DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
  ImageSize->{301.24441793024295`, 245.16817483064412`},
  ImageSizeRaw->{145.71810214077036`, 105.43133272538091`},
  PlotRange->{{0, 145.71810214077036`}, {0, 105.43133272538091`}}]], "Input",ExpressionUUID->"36d3e374-2b97-4ae3-8c7a-2cb679bcdf96"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 10.12",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Molecular orbital energy diagram for hydrogen fluoride. Wikimedia, 2019, \
Aixin805128565, CC BY-SA 4.0, \
https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:HF_MO_diagram.png."
}], "Affiliation",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809435027311596*^9, 3.8094350763900714`*^9}, {
  3.80943583474421*^9, 3.8094358359299717`*^9}, {3.8094472165104203`*^9, 
  3.809447281165168*^9}, {3.809510876137825*^9, 3.809510907739876*^9}, {
  3.809968073566992*^9, 3.8099681536568317`*^9}, {3.810557260250428*^9, 
  3.8105572606139913`*^9}, {3.8130835305386977`*^9, 3.8130836194514275`*^9}, {
  3.813224407772764*^9, 3.8132244817756805`*^9}, {3.814107987969291*^9, 
  3.814108049630145*^9}, {3.814109089245699*^9, 3.8141091270231557`*^9}, {
  3.8141093100266285`*^9, 3.814109310147791*^9}, {3.9196737815836964`*^9, 
  3.9196737824410815`*^9}, {3.937487983011875*^9, 
  3.9374879838978176`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"168080d7-57f4-4098-91cf-\
7d68838e17ff"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note that the linear combination of the H 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and F 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbitals yields a set of bonding and antibonding \[Sigma] molecular \
orbitals and two non-bonding ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals, which retain most of their F 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " character in the molecular orbital approximation. The origin of the \
\[Sigma] orbitals is illustrated in Figure 10.8 above, which shows a \
graphical representation of the combination of ",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["p", "z"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4d25b5be-ce2f-4b1c-b7a0-ae5e5ad606e9"],
 " orbitals, yielding a bonding \[Sigma] orbital. In contrast, the \
combination of  ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["p", "x"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c44a63c3-f3d0-4edd-89c3-deed20281ffb"],
 " orbital and ",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbital yields a net orbital overlap of zero, meaning that these orbitals \
do not mix."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141093232298574`*^9, 3.8141096483773556`*^9}, {
  3.919673815757068*^9, 3.9196738586813955`*^9}, {3.9374880000876007`*^9, 
  3.93748800125597*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b2dc725a-55a5-4802-b557-\
ed3bebdf197f"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Molecular Term Symbols", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814111967600335*^9, 
  3.814111970369979*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"cfe89f66-708c-484b-b934-\
6f6d3d3d98c9"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Components of a Molecular Term Symbol", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141120896826143`*^9, 
  3.8141121528217134`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"143ab955-56e0-4e7b-a232-\
cd8b72ea3764"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Just like atoms, molecules have term symbols that designate their \
electronic state. The molecular term symbols are composed of only two \
components: the total orbital angular momentum and the total spin. The total \
orbital angular momentum is the sum of the orbital angular momentum of each \
electron in the molecular orbitals and is given the symbol ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["M", "L"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "fd0877c5-8ba7-4ae0-96ad-3ae8f0a161b6"]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141121552114735`*^9, 3.814112239689965*^9}, {
  3.814112276316343*^9, 
  3.8141123525773125`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a25262b3-ffa2-4eb6-a9d8-\
0d6a30e9a5d2"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["M",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["L",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["m",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{
       StyleBox["l",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], "1"}]]], "+", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["m",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox["l2",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]], "+", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["m",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{
       StyleBox["l",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], "3"}]]], "+"}], 
   "..."}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141123703181643`*^9, 
  3.8141124105262985`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c639a272-3469-45ea-9d7c-\
2954eb003735"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The possible values of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["m", "l"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "04991cdb-01e4-4d72-97fa-5b05d007481c"],
 " are 0 for a \[Sigma] orbital and \[PlusMinus]1 for a \[Pi] orbital (that\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s all we\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll be concerned with at the \
moment). There is also a sum of the ",
 StyleBox["z",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "-components of the spin angular momentum of each electron ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["M", "s"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "3fed33b3-eb22-4818-bdff-2d0753a0a190"],
 ","
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814112415045236*^9, 3.8141124545971117`*^9}, {
  3.8141125656309595`*^9, 3.8141125657101755`*^9}, {3.8141125995602055`*^9, 
  3.814112694607623*^9}, {3.8141127540663276`*^9, 
  3.8141127819396925`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8149f89b-2919-4faf-bfa4-\
d0c240579f67"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["M",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["s",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["m",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{
       StyleBox["s",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], "1"}]]], "+", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["m",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox["s2",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]], "+", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["m",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{
       StyleBox["s",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], "3"}]]], "+"}], 
   "..."}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141123703181643`*^9, 3.8141124105262985`*^9}, {
  3.814112790168564*^9, 
  3.81411280072911*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c585827f-a048-4c9f-86d4-\
8bae8eb5113b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where the possible values of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["m",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["s",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141123703181643`*^9, 3.8141124105262985`*^9}, {
   3.814112790168564*^9, 3.81411280072911*^9}},ExpressionUUID->
  "f9bc236c-c035-40c4-ae7e-d88cfbab0f90"],
 " are ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "1"}], "/", "2"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"9cd9b4f3-0e56-44f8-8d85-ed79b5a6e3d2"],
 ". The spin quantum number ",
 StyleBox["S",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " has the same relationship to this total ",
 StyleBox["z",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " projection as in the atomic case, meaning ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["M",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["s",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141123703181643`*^9, 3.8141124105262985`*^9}, {
   3.814112790168564*^9, 3.81411280072911*^9}},ExpressionUUID->
  "c7af9267-8673-4b68-9003-8485c93186d7"],
 " can take on integer values from \[Minus]",
 StyleBox["S",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " to ",
 StyleBox["S",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". Combining these two pieces of information, the molecular term symbol is \
written as"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141128041914454`*^9, 3.814112807389056*^9}, {
  3.8141128845771723`*^9, 3.8141129371414304`*^9}, {3.81411300779784*^9, 
  3.81411306660314*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"beb9b51e-26f0-478e-8ec9-\
9f9a4434596d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SuperscriptBox[" ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"2", 
     StyleBox["S",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]}], "+", "1"}]], 
  RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["M",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], 
    StyleBox["L",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]], 
   "\[RightBracketingBar]"}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 
  3.8141130961037016`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"082fa8c8-9eaa-4140-934a-\
58110b349d1c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note that we use the absolute value of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["M",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["L",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"fd01caa5-83f1-4be8-a24b-bbaa1014100a"],
 ". In addition, we don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t actually write down the number \
associated with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["M",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["L",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"e189c7c6-abff-4457-8208-9ae91c61f1ee"],
 "; instead, we utilize a greek letter code to represent the value of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["M",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["L",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"9e844d25-9784-4d78-bd49-08f29438c167"],
 ","
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113101714867*^9, 
  3.8141131534019337`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a158811e-30e5-4b03-a8ab-\
b2f282b65ed3"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"\[NoBreak]", GridBox[{
    {
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["M",
         FontSlant->"Italic"], 
        StyleBox["L",
         FontSlant->"Italic"]], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}],
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "=", "0", "1", "2", "3"},
    {" ", " ", "\[CapitalSigma]", "\[CapitalPi]", "\[CapitalDelta]", 
     "\[CapitalPhi]"}
   }], "\[NoBreak]"}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8128108612387547`*^9, 3.8128108663038797`*^9}, {
  3.8128108967855253`*^9, 3.812810931478409*^9}, {3.8128110701849627`*^9, 
  3.8128111062398863`*^9}, {3.8141131706158667`*^9, 3.8141132254983516`*^9}, {
  3.8141799602300243`*^9, 
  3.814179962846346*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"89e79bb0-b064-4e88-a230-\
2ce9a06f48bb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "(that\[CloseCurlyQuote]s capital epsilon, pi, delta, and phi). Similar to \
the case of atomic orbitals, molecular orbitals containing two electrons (\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]filled\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] orbitals) have ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["M", "L"], "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "350c5dd4-82c2-4bff-90d6-75868eaf7557"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["M", "S"], "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a3b1db60-26ef-4d7f-a77b-d7d0236ae0b4"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"S", "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "6c29af86-09ab-471e-b80d-dcfad67aa78f"],
 ", so we don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t have to take them into account when \
assigning a molecular term symbol.  "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141132305581007`*^9, 3.814113260229748*^9}, {
  3.814113325891127*^9, 3.8141133343058653`*^9}, {3.81411344750931*^9, 
  3.814113555457068*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"078d2561-25c6-4283-9ad2-\
3daa62a0e7b6"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 "Example - Molecular Term Symbol of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["B",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b2f50429-31bb-4d57-84d8-4c16de8a7c10"]
}], "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141137733114867`*^9, 
  3.814113789581177*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"489a4bf6-fe6e-4c72-833f-\
1115b6f27b9b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s examine the exemplary case of the ground state \
electronic configuration of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["B",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "22f3bfd8-b8a9-499e-a1c7-32bd1c2c7997"],
 " with electron configuration ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"1", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "g"]}], ")"}], "2"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"1", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "u"]}], ")"}], "2"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"2", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "g"]}], ")"}], "2"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"2", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "u"]}], ")"}], "2"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"1", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Pi]", "u"]}], ")"}], "1"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"1", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Pi]", "u"]}], ")"}], "1"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"7341c7b9-9f76-4ead-96ff-db6ab7a39704"],
 ". Note that the prefixes 1 and 2 don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t denote the energy \
level, just the first occurrence of a \[Sigma] orbital, second occurrence of \
a \[Sigma] orbital, and first occurrence of a \[Pi] orbital. This is a more \
general nomenclature. We only need to concern ourselves with the two \
electrons in the two ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"1", 
    SubscriptBox["\[Pi]", "u"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b234fedb-b9c4-4969-86d4-74ebbc7ad119"],
 " (bonding) \[Pi] orbitals. Each can have a value of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["m", "l"], "=", 
    RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "1"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b7557b95-1ac7-49e1-b4c9-b126c07bd68b"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["m", "s"], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "1"}], "/", "2"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"99028815-4491-4ee8-955e-745e9776f96e"],
 ". That gives us possible values of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["M", "L"], "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"-", "2"}]}], ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "2"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"b70e6d92-7046-458c-8db9-f8bf9afcd2f9"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["M", "S"], "=", "1"}], ",", "0", ",", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4ec9cb5a-1cb9-46b9-acc1-28a9907ff313"],
 ". Once again, a table can help us in determining which configurations are \
allowed. Note that we cannot have two electrons with the same values of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["m", "l"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1c16887d-3a0c-4dbd-a417-d78f399453d4"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["m", "s"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a5e5a006-00ab-46d4-92a6-a8377323df16"],
 ", as this would mean they are in the same electronic state. Our possible \
configurations in table form are then"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814115234996934*^9, 3.8141152672489376`*^9}, {
  3.814115396162615*^9, 
  3.814115835107703*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e6ebd7f3-a681-49b0-87d2-\
062710956e7a"],

Cell[TextData[Cell[BoxData[GridBox[{
   {Cell[" ",ExpressionUUID->"783ebe5c-a95c-4568-8dd4-8e01e4488f71"], " ", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["M",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox["S",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]], " "},
   {
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["M",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox["L",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]], 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}], "0", "1"},
   {
    RowBox[{"-", "2"}], " ", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"-", 
       SuperscriptBox["1", "+"]}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"-", 
       SuperscriptBox["1", "\[Minus]"]}]}], ")"}], " "},
   {"0", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"-", 
       SuperscriptBox["1", "-"]}], ",", 
      SuperscriptBox["1", "-"]}], ")"}], 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["1", "+"], ",", 
       RowBox[{"-", 
        SuperscriptBox["1", "-"]}]}], ")"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["1", "-"], ",", 
       RowBox[{"-", 
        SuperscriptBox["1", "+"]}]}], ")"}]}], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"-", 
       SuperscriptBox["1", "+"]}], ",", 
      SuperscriptBox["1", "+"]}], ")"}]},
   {"2", " ", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox["1", "+"], ",", 
      SuperscriptBox["1", "\[Minus]"]}], ")"}], " "}
  },
  GridBoxDividers->{
   "Columns" -> {{True}}, 
    "Rows" -> {{
      True}}}]],ExpressionUUID->"a9d340ee-dbf7-46b0-9463-ae1fdffffb73"]], \
"Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.812816183242498*^9, 3.812816428079652*^9}, {
  3.812816462800923*^9, 3.8128166290840225`*^9}, {3.81281717239036*^9, 
  3.812817174537908*^9}, {3.8141158570635295`*^9, 
  3.8141158667916374`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"36d2bbe8-4218-4cfb-84d1-\
a94a44374441"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "From the middle row of this table, we see that there is a set of electron \
configurations with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["M", "L"], "=", " ", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2b55ecd3-4705-4468-ba6c-06fd4f912870"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["M", "S"], "=", "1"}], ",", "0", ",", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "65f8a5b0-56b0-4b59-bf70-6f2a6ed32178"],
 ", giving a value of ",
 StyleBox["S",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " of 1 and a term symbol of"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814115883358034*^9, 3.814115890589572*^9}, {
  3.8141159259651566`*^9, 
  3.8141159858156514`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d8963fab-714e-4174-9e6e-\
550feaf8504c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SuperscriptBox[" ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"2", 
     RowBox[{"(", "1", ")"}]}], "+", "1"}]], 
  RowBox[{
  "\[LeftBracketingBar]", "0", 
   "\[RightBracketingBar]"}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
  3.8141159713246417`*^9, 
  3.814115989361409*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6be8ba18-fd09-4cb7-890f-\
04944d011abf"],

Cell["or", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141159948425083`*^9, 
  3.814115994963414*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"dcddbbc9-c406-4b14-95b4-\
a0377240e311"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SuperscriptBox[" ", "3"], "\[CapitalSigma]"}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
  3.8141160072363405`*^9, 
  3.8141160194416428`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"191c4c09-0003-48ef-95a6-\
e8a4af3d7061"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "There are three remaining configurations in our table, all in the middle \
column with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["M", "S"], "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b18ed747-edb0-4231-bbca-04f36a3534a7"],
 ". Note that we don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t have an ",
 StyleBox["L",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " value in our molecular term symbol, we just have the absolute value of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["M", "L"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "cb21a4f2-405a-4547-aa1d-de77d1939d15"],
 ". Two of these remaining states have ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["M",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox["L",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], "=", "2"}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"64137f8a-46b6-41ed-ac6d-5489835cd5bc"],
 " (those with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["M",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], 
    StyleBox["L",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]], "=", 
   RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "2"}]}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"fe181739-3b43-4a74-9d63-ef08cabe7674"],
 ") and have a term symbol of"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141160266437025`*^9, 
  3.8141162104862947`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3f164e5e-242a-4ca6-822b-\
6731ab0a6767"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SuperscriptBox[" ", "1"], "\[CapitalDelta]"}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
  3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141162178627195`*^9, 
  3.8141162279598026`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"942cd726-3378-4a14-9dee-\
e8ebd1cbed78"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The final remaining configuration has ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["M",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox["L",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], "=", "0"}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"2cfecf03-ff37-4170-bee0-e1d86ae2384b"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["M", "S"], "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f21e97bb-f1ce-45d7-8134-e0954e8fc739"],
 ", giving a term symbol of"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.81411623203825*^9, 
  3.814116256823485*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5c5e18b5-dccf-411f-b63c-\
60708129511b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SuperscriptBox[" ", "1"], "\[CapitalSigma]"}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
   3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141162178627195`*^9, 
   3.8141162279598026`*^9}, 
   3.814116287061685*^9},ExpressionUUID->"541021fb-0e3b-47f3-b79c-\
733a215ad886"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We can also use Hund\[CloseCurlyQuote]s rules to find the lowest-energy \
configuration of a molecule, and we find that the state with term symbol ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[" ", "3"], "\[CapitalSigma]"}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
   3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->
  "d3d757d3-91a0-4e59-9dac-810766c33a05"],
 " (highest spin multiplicity) is the ground state."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141162894750786`*^9, 
  3.8141163354545865`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ff3a1410-a564-4168-aaa5-\
44f9cbe22776"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Symmetry Designations in Molecular Term Symbols", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141163795771823`*^9, 
  3.8141163903813486`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"526ffcbb-d144-4c47-b7be-\
4c4d340a87d2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In addition to the main term symbols, there are two additional components \
of molecular term symbols that you might encounter (at least for homonuclear \
diatomic molecules or other highly symmetric molecules). The first concerns \
the topic of ",
 StyleBox["gerade",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["ungerade",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals that we already discussed briefly. Molecular term symbols can \
also be given a designation of ",
 StyleBox["gerade",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " (",
 StyleBox["g",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ") or ",
 StyleBox["ungerade",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " (",
 StyleBox["u",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "). To find this value, one simply multiplies the symmetry of all of the \
unfilled orbitals. The rules are "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141163923905706`*^9, 
  3.814116562931077*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"bbbf2c27-de72-477e-bb14-\
c3f3af3f19eb"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["g",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[CenterDot]", 
   StyleBox["g",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]}], " ", "=", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["g",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["      ",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"even", " ", "times", " ", "even", " ", "is", " ", "even"}], 
    ")"}]}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["u",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[CenterDot]", 
   StyleBox["g",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]}], " ", "=", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["u",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["      ",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"odd", " ", "times", " ", "even", " ", "is", " ", "odd"}], 
    ")"}]}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["u",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[CenterDot]", 
   StyleBox["u",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]}], " ", "=", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["g",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["      ",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"odd", " ", "times", " ", "odd", " ", "is", " ", "even"}], 
    ")"}]}]}]}], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
   3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141162178627195`*^9, 
   3.8141162279598026`*^9}, 3.814116287061685*^9, {3.8141165770230427`*^9, 
   3.8141166595236034`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"42afb674-7484-435f-bae9-\
0ea069780c4a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For example, for ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["B",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "691865ea-8489-43ea-be9b-289ca0839cf7"],
 ", we have the unfilled orbitals as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["u",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[CenterDot]", 
     StyleBox["u",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]}], " ", "=", " ", 
    StyleBox["g",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a8c74ad2-5bb3-4700-bf07-17dfc0025d05"],
 ", so the overall term symbol is ",
 StyleBox["g",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". This component is written as a subscript, e.g.,"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814116664268746*^9, 
  3.8141167459755144`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5d5b7bb4-6f4b-4958-a3e9-\
e85e51cb8053"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SuperscriptBox[" ", "3"], 
  SubscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", 
   StyleBox["g",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
  3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141167533132515`*^9, 
  3.814116753880442*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9a7bae2a-bfad-44cd-aff1-\
9115c906f5b5"],

Cell["\<\
Remember that these labels are specifying symmetry with respect to inversion \
of the wavefunction about some central point of symmetry.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814116764144022*^9, 
  3.8141167902256575`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1413ccc1-3d4b-47ed-b5d6-\
2e038650ac64"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A second symmetry label that might be encountered represents the behavior \
of a wavefunction when inverted through a plane of symmetry that (in the case \
of homonuclear diatomic molecules) contains both nuclei. If the wavefunction \
of the molecular orbital changes sign during this operation, then the orbital \
is given the designation \[Minus], whereas if it doesn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t \
change sign, it is given the designation +. Since \[Sigma] orbitals are \
symmetric with respect to the internuclear plane, they will always be +. For \
\[Pi] molecular orbitals, one \[Pi] orbital will be \[Minus] and one will be \
+ (which one depends on the designation of the plane of symmetry). Using the \
example of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["B",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "796bf990-fbda-45ab-b3bb-5cafc5874f89"],
 " once more, we have two \[Pi] orbitals, one + and one \[Minus], so our \
overall symmetry designation is (+)(\[Minus]) = (\[Minus]). This component of \
the term symbol is designated with a superscript,"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814116813094557*^9, 3.8141171036754727`*^9}, {
  3.814180816037447*^9, 
  3.814180817487526*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"572fd339-5d37-4503-a277-\
3b570fc29106"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SuperscriptBox[" ", "3"], 
  SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", 
   StyleBox["g",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[Minus]"]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
  3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141167533132515`*^9, 
  3.814116753880442*^9}, {3.8141171111247144`*^9, 
  3.814117113269617*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9741d37a-2cd4-4958-b3ec-\
5a31d6b7fb04"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Term Symbols and Excited States", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814117165999794*^9, 
  3.8141171719768476`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"73e93e39-3180-47c0-8f9b-\
be07d9e6d593"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We can also use term symbols to differentiate between electronically \
excited states. Take the case of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["H",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5e20d75e-609a-49bc-9080-f227ee848485"],
 ". The ground state of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["H",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "6e64b68d-480d-4ccb-8dcf-71b34d350ef1"],
 " has a fully filled orbital ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"1", 
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "g"]}], ")"}], "2"], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"c3f4b2c2-3e23-452f-bdb0-9f27cb746028"],
 " and thus a term symbol of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[" ", "1"], 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", 
    StyleBox["g",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "+"]}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
   3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141167533132515`*^9, 
   3.814116753880442*^9}, {3.8141171111247144`*^9, 3.814117113269617*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"0a5a6782-f2ae-4bd3-a781-f95c6b64ef18"],
 ". When one electron is promoted to the first antibonding orbital, giving an \
electron configuration of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"1", 
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "g"]}], ")"}], "1"], 
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"1", 
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "u"]}], ")"}], "1"]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "71d928c7-762e-42d7-b2ff-273e2f1e3ee5"],
 ", there are two possible term symbols: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[" ", "3"], 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", 
    StyleBox["u",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "+"]}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
   3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141167533132515`*^9, 
   3.814116753880442*^9}, {3.8141171111247144`*^9, 3.814117113269617*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"78b8a6dc-3ed4-4fb4-9a0e-75d8f743bfcc"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[" ", "1"], 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", 
    StyleBox["u",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "+"]}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
   3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141167533132515`*^9, 
   3.814116753880442*^9}, {3.8141171111247144`*^9, 3.814117113269617*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"31038a85-45d8-4220-8b9c-c1d8ab2dca2e"],
 ". A higher-energy excited state is given by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"1", 
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "g"]}], ")"}], "1"], 
   FormBox[
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"2", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "g"]}], ")"}], "1"],
    TraditionalForm]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "6723fec5-c2ba-4244-891a-ba8523994ba7"],
 ", with term symbol ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[" ", "1"], 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", 
    StyleBox["g",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "+"]}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
   3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141167533132515`*^9, 
   3.814116753880442*^9}, {3.8141171111247144`*^9, 3.814117113269617*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"4bc48cf1-f4a2-4598-a5e0-5f41dc6ec6f5"],
 ". Note that this state is bound, whereas the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[" ", "3"], 
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", 
    StyleBox["u",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "+"]}]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814113073313775*^9, 3.8141130961037016`*^9}, {
   3.8141160072363405`*^9, 3.8141160194416428`*^9}, {3.8141167533132515`*^9, 
   3.814116753880442*^9}, {3.8141171111247144`*^9, 3.814117113269617*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"d92cda78-ad56-4b4c-ba84-a8d0ab5c5df4"],
 " is repulsive, as shown in Figure 10.13. However, the excited state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"1", 
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "g"]}], ")"}], "1"], 
   FormBox[
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"2", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "g"]}], ")"}], "1"],
    TraditionalForm]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "512eee6b-a924-42ac-ae6f-4a95f7283f0f"],
 " has a longer bond length, as can be visualized by the difference in the \
minima of the internuclear potentials in Figure 10.13. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8141171746143303`*^9, 3.8141173409685555`*^9}, {
  3.8141173792510157`*^9, 3.8141175291688733`*^9}, {3.8141175933792157`*^9, 
  3.814117641964677*^9}, {3.9196745265240936`*^9, 3.919674535672546*^9}, {
  3.9374880548041115`*^9, 
